^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at| As usual I should make it clear that this tutorial is solely for my learning. To prepare it I have used several sources--listed on the opening page. Howard kindly has guided me through out its preparation. No, I did not ask permission to use the material from those sources as almost all are in Wikipedia.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


at|

There are several explanations for the principle of restricted choice. Most notables are by Terence Reese and by Andrew Robson. However, it is very difficult to find a comprehensive and all inclusive definition without going through pages of examples and probability charts. A Google Search produces couple hundred links for the item which in most part are copied from a few original sources. They all have a rather lengthy and complicated explanation starting with a set of card combinations and most lead to describing the famous TV show by Monty Hall--let us make a deal. |
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT|

Further, it is rather tedious to have a good distinction between the "Eight ever Nine never" rule and the restricted choice principle. Nevertheless, I like a few of them which I will share them here with you to develop the base for what I hope would be a short and easy to understand explanation--at least for us bridge challenged. But, first, let us look at the easy and familiar "Eight ever Nine never" rule.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

"Eight ever - Nine never" Rule deals with whether you should finesse a missing ^*BQueen^*N when you have a 8-card or when you have a 9-card fit in a suit. With just eight cards you should always finesse--eight ever; but with nine cards you should play for the drop--nine never (finesse). But actually the odds for nine cards are very close and you may prefer to finesse if there was an inference that may be working. Further please note that it usually deals with a combination of cards missing only the Queen with three or four spots. Also, the rule can be ignored when additional information from the bidding, the play if the cards from other suits, from the opening lead, or from the second play in the particular suit becomes available. And finally it is static.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


AT|

On the other hand, the restricted choice  is complex and difficult to define properly in a few paragraphs. Next, you will find several of the better ones.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||
