ht|d|va|8|CS||FP||CP||AT|^B@2^Y@3"The principle of restricted choice is an idea from probability. It is related to the idea of Bayesian inference and the idea of biased information."|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


AT|

"The Principle of restricted choice is used in bridge to guide a player (usually the declarer) into finding the best line of play in certain situations."|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


AT|

"A mathematically based guideline for analyzing suit combinations. In general, the guideline states that a play of a card which may have been selected as a choice of equal plays increases the chance that the player started with a holding in which his choice was restricted.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT|

"Crucially, it helps play, in situations which used to be thought of as guesswork. In many of those situations the rule derived from the principle is to play for split honors. After observing one equivalent card, that is, one should continue play as if two equivalents were split between the opposing players, so that there was no choice about which one to play. Whoever played the first one doesn't have the other one."|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


AT|

"The most common example of what restricted choice principle is all about usually revolves around a combination of cards in one suit"|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


at|

"Restricted choice is based on a complex mathematical situation and comes into play based on a known information--when two touching honors or equivalent honors are missing and gaining additional information--when one of the touching honors appears on the first round of play. It gives the declarer a 2 to 1 odds to gain the maximum number of tricks possible from a suit combination."|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||
