ht|d|va|8|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|Simply, restricted choice principle is appropriate when the declarer playing a card from a nine-card fit in a suit and a defender dropping one of the two ^*BMISSING touching honors^*N on the first round. Then, the declarer should play the other defender for the other missing touching honor. This is the best line of play by 2 to 1 odds. We will get to the logic behind the principle later. All we have to remember for now is:  |
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


AT|

^ba) The missing honors should be touching and 
^bb) One of them should be played by one of the defenders on the first round.|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


AT|

Based on my reviewing all the explanations, the restricted choice has ALL the following properties. If one is missing so goes the restricted choice principle out the window.|
PG| ***** 36 ***** |


AT|

A. It usually deals with suit combinations missing at least two touching honors--Ace-King, King-Queen, Queen-Jack, or Jack-Ten. The case of missing Queen--Jack is more often and most important.

B. It is a dynamic phenomenon-requires one round of play in that suit with one of the missing honors to appear.

C. In most instances, using the restricted choice principle give the declarer a two to one odds of making the maximum number of the tricks in the 9-card suit combination. But again it is not 100 percent.|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


AT|

